    {
      "id": "090d5ebf54bbf9070ce941723b0dc68f5e3e73d5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-04 10:10:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "3ec6fbbdf5feab68e794194d67d7e669dc21e490",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-04 10:11:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nwe can discuss this here or in email or on skype, up to you.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "9d41a2aa759a62ef1a88c060cdd72316eb92927d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-04 21:55:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nAlex, I would argue that aborting all scrub activity because of a single error is not very useful.  The whole point of OI scrub and LFSCK is to repair a filesystem that is inconsistent for some reason.  It is entirely possible that some kinds of unrecoverable error will be hit on fixing a single OI entry, but that only affects a single file, and the rest of the OI should be repaired as best it can be after recording and/or reporting an error.\n\nSimilarly, the LFSCK object iteration needs to continue so that it can repair the distributed filesystem state as much as possible.\n\nI think that part of the disagreement between Alex & Fan Yong is that Alex wants a \"bottom up\" approach to the OI Scrub patches, something like:\n- implement the inode iterator with a simple no-op user\n- implement the OI scrub/repair inside the OSD only\n- rate control inside OSD also rate controls callers\n- implement MDD-level inode iterator on top of OSD index ops\n\nAlex, we need to get past this impasse where you disagree with every patch of Fan Yong's.  Can you two please get on the phone and discuss specifics of how this functionality can be implemented in a manner that is agreeable to both of you.  If we need to set up a larger meeting, then please arrange with Richard/Bryon so that this can move forward.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "d683a958c77c821445db2a61c1f9f96a8eb97e85",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-05 04:00:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Alex, I would argue that aborting all scrub activity because of a single error is not very useful.  The whole point of OI scrub and LFSCK is to repair a filesystem that is inconsistent for some reason.  It is entirely possible that some kinds of unrecoverable error will be hit on fixing a single OI entry, but that only affects a single file, and the rest of the OI should be repaired as best it can be after recording and/or reporting an error\n\nI'm not saying all the activity should be stopped due to a single error - it's up to OSD to decide whether OI rebuild/scrub should continue or stop. but once it's stopped there is no any point for MDD to proceeed, right ? this is where the iterator can return an error?\n\n\n> I think that part of the disagreement between Alex & Fan Yong is that Alex wants a \"bottom up\" approach to the OI Scrub patches, something like:\n\ncorrect. I think this separation should make things simpler. if this is not possible, then I'd like to know why. and just logically: OI scrub basically repair objects in lustre terms (they get fids), then it becomes possible for LFSCK to access the objects, correct distributed state.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
