    {
      "id": "30f69d4fd38a86c52f53348629421d9650df468e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-05 15:53:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "2f31fcf8c10c5e75e5e07ff76952f98a7fddd872",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 04:33:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nAlex, I typically agree with your statements. One thing to clarify - there are two mechanisms by which an inode traversal are initiated.\n\nFirst when the OSD starts up and detects that an OI is missing, or if during runtime it is detected that an OI entry is incorrect (e.g. inode is missing or has wrong FID in LMA, I don't think the cost of checking this on the first read from disk would be too much).\n\nThe second reason an inode iteration (not an OI iteration as you wrote) is if there is a consistency scan and/or distributed repair. This is not the OI that is opened, but should instead be a local FID that represents a virtual index with all of the inodes in it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1e3cb8b514e4a560bef373398f8e1c21886be6ca",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 06:53:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> The second reason an inode iteration (not an OI iteration as you wrote) is if there is a consistency scan and/or distributed repair. This is not the OI that is opened, but should instead be a local FID that represents a virtual index with all of the inodes in it.\n\nI don't understand why it should be a local fid, please clarify. \n\nit's important that accessing the same object with different fids we create an alias which can result in some badness because all the locking is done on per-object basis.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "3a9a49c45d8194f09bbe416a198953a770406255",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 07:02:47.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 5.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "c91f5f0c08f57ec7e9c1768fbb33230d27b30af9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 07:17:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nRebase against the laster master branch.\n\n1) Any object which will be used when Lustre server mounts should not be added into OI files to guarantee that the Lustre server can startup even if OI files corrupt.\n\n2) Drop all special return values defined for LFSCK dt iteration API \"next()\", which was objected by Alex in former inspections. Currently, the low layer dt iteration API \"next()\" just returns the standard \"+1/0/error\" for LFSCK iteration, totally the same as other non-LFSCK iteration does, neither special value defined by LFSCK nor special error code to notify something.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "e670d16cf8c1bff05df3b349a6725df9c633000d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 07:53:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nAlex, my comment was mainly that you were incorrectly referring to \"OI iteration\", but OI scrub/LFSCK are doing \"inode table iteration\".  In order for LFSCK to do inode table iteration, it needs to open some local FID as index that contains all inodes in the filesystem.  The inodes themselves will still use their normal FIDs, only the \"all inodes\" FID is treated specially.\n\nMy thought is that whenever LFSCK opens this special FID the OSD should start the OI verification.  Then, no other API is needed between LFSCK and OSD to signal scrub handling.  Of course, the OSD can do an urgent OI scrub itself if it finds an error internally (FID->OI->inode->LMA_FID mismatch or missing/broken OI file).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "7518939df1c239cc2323469cfb16215b56a91e79",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-06 08:03:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Alex, my comment was mainly that you were incorrectly referring to \"OI iteration\", but OI scrub/LFSCK are doing \"inode table iteration\". In order for LFSCK to do inode table iteration, it needs to open some local FID as index that contains all inodes in the filesystem. The inodes themselves will still use their normal FIDs, only the \"all inodes\" FID is treated specially.\n\nwell, of course this is inode table iteration. I just thought it's probably a bit simpler wording to express that LFSCK iterates over verified pairs of fid/ino. no disagreement here.\n\n\n> My thought is that whenever LFSCK opens this special FID the OSD should start the OI verification. Then, no other API is needed between LFSCK and OSD to signal scrub handling. Of course, the OSD can do an urgent OI scrub itself if it finds an error internally (FID->OI->inode->LMA_FID mismatch or missing/broken OI file).\n\nabsolutely agree.\n\nbasically this is the same code where one if() makes it behave different: if LFSCK is running (iterating over ... that special fid :), then block and don't run too far away ?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
